{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774458201,"nonce":"zM85eF8COr1sF757o1Ue5jrcvp0=","title":"Part 2 analysis: null-space decomposition of SISU effects","message":"Umbrella: 0af472c (Part 2)\n\n**Motivation:** The central hypothesis of the SISU mechanism is that the network can modulate its internal state in response to SISU without changing its motor output -- i.e., SISU effects live in the output-null space of the readout. This analysis directly tests that hypothesis by decomposing SISU-induced state changes into potent (output-affecting) and null (output-preserving) components.\n\n**Approach:**\n1. Compute the readout weight matrix W and its null space N = null(W).\n2. At steady state: vary SISU and measure the resulting change in hidden state dh. Project dh onto the potent space (row space of W) and null space. If SISU acts in the null space, the potent projection should be near zero.\n3. During reaching: repeat the decomposition along the trajectory. SISU may need to use the potent space transiently (e.g., to modulate feedback gains that affect force output), but the null-space fraction should still be large.\n4. Compare with the `sisu_pert` module results: the null-space analysis provides the mechanistic explanation for why SISU step changes affect neural activity but not steady-state force output.\n\n**Status:** No module exists yet. The infrastructure is available: `fps_steady` already computes steady-state FPs for different SISU levels, and `sisu_pert` demonstrates the behavioral null-space property. This analysis provides the linear algebra to explain it.\n\n**References:** Kaufman et al. (2014) for output-potent vs output-null decomposition; Hennequin et al. (2014) for null-space control.","files":null}]}